The popular Police Mammy Market in Damaturu, Yobe State, has been closed over fears of bomb attack by Boko Haram. The Damaturu Police Mammy Market is located inside the Police Area Command, Damaturu. Our correspondent ,who visited the market, confirmed that all shops at the market were under lock and key, a situation that looked contrary to the booming nightlife in Damaturu, the state capital.   Three dead, many injured in Ibadan clash     I mistook 78-year-old for antelope, hunter tells police     Police seek legal advice on Osinachi autopsy report   Boko Haram last Wednesday slaughtered  12 people in Giedam town at a drinking facility and a few days later launched  a bomb attack on another bar in  Gashua town, home of Senate president Ahmed Lawan,  killing one person and injuring seven. Other pubs in the town, especially in Jerusalem area, have also been shut for the same reasons. A security source said the market  will remain closed and until adequate security measures were put in place. Police spokesman  Dungus Abdulkareem confirmed the closure of the market, saying “The Police do not want to be embarrassed  or caught unawares by these terrorists”.